      "rationale": "Three-level GCI study yields GCI = 2.1% on the fine mesh for the shear-stress power-law hemolysis index. Richardson extrapolation applied. Discretization error is within the accepted threshold for MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Laboratory test conditions documented with controlled fluid temperature, flow rate, and rotational speed; deviations from nominal reported.",
      "rationale": "All five operating points tested at 22°C ± 0.5°C, flow rates controlled to ± 0.05 L/min, and rotational speed controlled to ± 20 RPM. Fluid temperature, ambient pressure (101.3 kPa), and blood preparation protocol are fully documented. Note: test conditions represent a single fixed laboratory environment; the effect of the broader clinical deployment environment (18–26°C, variable pressure, EM interference) on these test conditions has not been evaluated."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric defined; predicted RH within 15% of measured RH for all operating points.",
      "rationale": "Relative hemolysis index predicted by CFD compared against experimental measurements at all 5 operating points. Maximum discrepancy is 9.3% (operating point 3, 4 L/min, 3000 RPM). All predictions satisfy RH < 1 acceptance criterion relative to predicate device. Comparison performed exclusively at 22°C laboratory conditions."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoI (relative hemolysis index) is directly linked to the clinical decision criterion and is measurable in both simulation and experiment.",
      "rationale": "The relative hemolysis index RH is the regulatory-accepted metric for comparative hemolysis assessment of CPB devices. It is directly computable from CFD shear stress fields via the Giersiepen power-law model and is directly measurable in vitro. The QoI is appropriate for the COU decision."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments use the same pump geometry, fluid, and operating points as the COU; any differences are documented and their impact assessed.",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments used the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry identical to the COU model geometry. Bovine blood at 22°C was used as a surrogate for human blood; a viscosity correction factor of 1.03 is applied and documented. The 5 flow-speed combinations span the clinical operating envelope. However, the validation activities were conducted exclusively under controlled laboratory conditions (22°C, 101.3 kPa, no EM interference), and no study has been conducted to assess whether the environmental variability present in actual surgical suite deployment (temperature range 18–26°C, altitude-dependent pressure, electromagnetic fields from electrosurgical units) materially affects the model predictions or the correspondence between simulation and physical behavior."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence demonstrated; residuals below solver-recommended thresholds for all simulations.",
      "rationale": "All simulations converged to residuals below 1×10⁻⁵ for continuity and momentum equations. Mass imbalance across the rotating domain interface is less than 0.01%. Convergence histories are archived."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation setup reviewed by an analyst independent of the primary modeler; boundary conditions traceable to documented COU inputs.",
      "rationale": "Independent analyst review of boundary condition specification, turbulence model selection (SST k-ω), and post-processing scripts completed prior to final results submission. No discrepancies identified. Boundary conditions are traceable to the COU operating envelope specification."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Governing equations and constitutive models documented and justified for the flow regime and QoI.",
      "rationale": "Reynolds-averaged Navier-Stokes with SST k-ω turbulence closure selected based on published literature for rotating blood pump CFD. Non-Newtonian blood rheology modeled using the Carreau-Yasuda model with parameters fit to 22°C bovine blood viscometry data. Hemolysis computed via Giersiepen power-law model. Model form assumptions are documented and consistent with FDA guidance on CFD for blood-contacting devices."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All model inputs (geometry, fluid properties, boundary conditions) characterized with uncertainty bounds; sensitivity of QoI to input uncertainty evaluated.",
      "rationale": "Geometric uncertainty from manufacturing tolerances (±0.05 mm on impeller clearances) propagated through a one-at-a-time sensitivity study. Fluid viscosity uncertainty (±3%) assessed. Rotational speed and flow rate boundary condition uncertainty assessed. Combined input uncertainty contributes ±6.2% to predicted RH. All input characterization was performed at 22°C laboratory conditions; temperature-dependent viscosity variation across the clinical deployment range (18–26°C) was not included in the uncertainty budget, as the model inputs were not varied to reflect deployment environmental conditions."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Blood samples characterized for hematocrit and viscosity; sample preparation protocol documented.",
      "rationale": "Fresh bovine blood obtained from a single USDA-inspected facility; hematocrit 38 ± 2%, viscosity measured at 22°C. Sample preparation protocol (anticoagulation with heparin, storage time < 4 hours) documented. Three independent sample batches used across the five operating points to assess batch-to-batch variability."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation input parameters match experimental test conditions within documented tolerances; any mismatches quantified.",
      "rationale": "CFD boundary conditions set to match measured experimental flow rates and rotational speeds within ± 1%. Fluid properties in simulation matched to measured blood viscosity at 22°C. Geometric model derived from CMM-measured pump dimensions. All parameter correspondences documented in the V&V report. The equivalency assessment is limited to the laboratory test conditions (22°C, 101.3 kPa); no equivalency evaluation has been performed for the range of environmental conditions (18–26°C, 86–101 kPa, EM interference) present in the intended clinical deployment environment."
    }
  ],
